1 ISL Exercise 8.4.3 (10pts)

# Generate sequence of pËm1 values
p_m1 <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.01)

# Calculate corresponding values of Gini index, classification error, and entropy
gini <- 2 * p_m1 * (1 - p_m1)
classification_error <- 1 - pmax(p_m1, 1 - p_m1)
entropy <- -p_m1 * log2(p_m1) - (1 - p_m1) * log2(1 - p_m1)

# Plot
plot(p_m1, gini, type = "l", col = "red", ylim = c(0, 1), xlab = "pËm1", ylab = "Value", main = "Gini Index, Classification Error, and Entropy")
lines(p_m1, classification_error, type = "l", col = "blue")
lines(p_m1, entropy, type = "l", col = "green")
legend("topright", legend = c("Gini Index", "Classification Error", "Entropy"), col = c("red", "blue", "green"), lty = 1)

4.3 Regression tree

4.3.1 Recipe

tree_recipe <- 
  recipe(
    medv ~ ., 
    data = Boston_other
  ) %>%
  # # create traditional dummy variables (not necessary for random forest in R)
  # step_dummy(all_nominal()) %>%
  step_naomit(medv) %>%
  # zero-variance filter
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  # # center and scale numeric data (not necessary for random forest)
  # step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  # estimate the means and standard deviations
  prep(training = Boston_other, retain = TRUE)
tree_recipe

4.3.2 Model

regtree_mod <- decision_tree(
  cost_complexity = tune(),
  tree_depth = tune(),
  min_n = 5,
  mode = "regression",
  engine = "rpart"
  )

4.3.4 Tuning grid

ccp_alpha is the Minimal Cost-Complexity Pruning parameter. Greater values of ccp_alpha increase the number of nodes pruned.

tree_grid <- grid_regular(cost_complexity(),
                          tree_depth(),
                          levels = c(100, 5))

rf_mod <- 
  rand_forest(
    mode = "regression",
    # Number of predictors randomly sampled in each split
    mtry = tune(),
    # Number of trees in ensemble
    trees = tune()
  ) %>% 
  set_engine("ranger")

4.5.1 Recipe

  recipe(
    medv ~ ., 
    data = Boston_other
  ) %>%
  # # create traditional dummy variables (not necessary for random forest in R)
  # step_dummy(all_nominal()) %>%
  step_naomit(medv) %>%
  # zero-variance filter
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  # # center and scale numeric data (not necessary for random forest)

5.3 Classification tree

5.3.1 Recipe

tree_recipe <- 
  recipe(
    Sales ~ ., 
    data = Carseats_other
  ) %>%
  step_naomit(all_predictors()) %>%
  # # create traditional dummy variables (not necessary for random forest in R)
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  # zero-variance filter
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  # # center and scale numeric data (not necessary for random forest)
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  # estimate the means and standard deviations
  prep(training = Carseats_other, retain = TRUE)
tree_recipe

5.5 Boosting

5.5.1 Recipe

gb_recipe <- 
  recipe(
    Sales ~ ., 
    data = Carseats_other
  ) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  prep(training = Carseats_other, retain = TRUE)
gb_recipe

5.5.2 Model

gb_mod <- 
  boost_tree(
    mode = "classification",
    trees = 1000, 
    tree_depth = tune(),
    learn_rate = tune()
  ) %>% 
  set_engine("xgboost")
gb_mod

  learn_rate = tune()
